[32.406902, "o", "cat finding.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[32.407764, "o", "=== IPTABLES HTTP BLOCKING ANALYSIS ===\r\n\r\nBLOCKING RULE IDENTIFIED:\r\nRules 4-7 in the INPUT chain are causing the HTTP/HTTPS traffic blockage:\r\n\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\r\nWHY HTTP IS BLOCKED BUT SSH IS NOT:\r\n\r\n1. SSH (port 22) has a simple unconditional ACCEPT rule:\r\n   -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT\r\n   This accepts ALL TCP traffic to port 22 regardless of packet content.\r\n\r\n2. HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443) use string matching that only accepts packets\r\n   containing the string \"Mozilla\" in the payload. This appears to be an\r\n   attempt at user-agent based filtering (likely trying to block bots/scanners).\r\n\r\n3. When curl connects without a custom User-Agent, it sends \"curl/X.X.X\" by\r\n   default, which does NOT contain \"Mozilla\". The packet fails the string match,\r\n   falls through to the DROP rule, and i"]
[32.407813, "o", "s silently discarded.\r\n\r\n4. The connection hangs (rather than getting \"connection refused\") because:\r\n   - The SYN packet from curl reaches the server\r\n   - Rule 2 (-m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT) doesn't apply yet\r\n   - The string matching happens on the packet payload level\r\n   - The DROP rule silently discards packets, causing curl to timeout waiting\r\n     for a response\r\n\r\nWHAT SHOULD BE CHANGED:\r\n\r\nThe string matching approach is fundamentally flawed because:\r\n\r\n1. It attempts to inspect application-layer data (User-Agent headers) at the\r\n   network layer, which is unreliable and breaks legitimate tools like curl,\r\n   wget, APIs, monitoring systems, etc.\r\n\r\n2. The string match occurs on raw packet data, not parsed HTTP headers, making\r\n   it fragile and easy to bypass.\r\n\r\n3. It blocks legitimate traffic while providing minimal security benefit (any\r\n   attacker can trivially add \"Mozilla\" to their User-Agent).\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDATION:\r\nRemove the string matching rules entirely and use proper ap"]
[32.407848, "o", "plication-layer\r\nfiltering (WAF, reverse proxy with UA filtering) if user-agent based blocking\r\nis truly needed. Alternatively, use connection rate limiting with connlimit\r\nor recent modules instead of content inspection at the iptables level.\r\n"]
